  "NewStyles" -> True, "CitationPopupData" -> {"2021", ""}, "ShowCitation" -> 
  False, "RootCaptions" -> "", "HeaderCoreAreaLink" -> {}, 
  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 4, 12, 17, 59, 57.771806}", 
    "history" -> {"13", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {"controlled-unitary gate", "two-level unitary matrix"}, 
    "specialkeywords" -> {}, "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True,
     "label" -> "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Tech Note", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "A multi-control unitary gate is a natural generalization of a \
controlled-unitary gate, where the single control and target qubit are \
replaced by respective registers of multiple qubits. With m and n qubits in \
the control and target registers, respectively, and a unitary operator U on \
the target register, the m-control n-target U gate is defined by the mapping \
TemplateBox[{c}, Ket]\\[CircleTimes]TemplateBox[{t}, \
Ket]\\[RightTeeArrow]TemplateBox[{c}, Ket]\\[CircleTimes](U^c_1c_ \
2\\[CenterEllipsis]c_mTemplateBox[{t}, Ket]) , where c\\[Congruent](c_ 1c_ \
2\\[CenterEllipsis] c_m)_ 2 and t\\[Congruent](t_ 1t_ 2\\[CenterEllipsis] \
t_n)_ 2. The unitary operator U on the target register takes effects only \
when every qubit in the control register is set to state |1\:27e9. In the \
quantum circuit model, a multi-control unitary gate is represented as where \
m=3 and n=2 have been assumed form the particular concrete example. Later we \
will see that the single-target case is sufficient to implement any unitary \
gate on multiple qubits, so here we will focus on it. In this case, the \
matrix representation takes the form in Figure 1 below.", "synonyms" -> {}, 
    "tabletags" -> {}, "title" -> "Multi-Control Unitary Gates", 
    "titlemodifier" -> "", "metadescription" -> "", "windowtitle" -> 
    "Multi-Control Unitary Gates", "type" -> "Tech Note", "uri" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/MultiControlUnitaryGates"}},
